AGI - A 46-year-old worker lost his life at night in an accident at work in the sugar mill in Brindisi. The worker, dependent on an external company that was carrying out maintenance work on the rig of the plant, was of Latiano, in Brindisino. The incident, in which the worker underwent the amplification of an arto, happened after midnight, but still it is not clear the dynamic, on which they investigate the forces of order. The man died shortly after the arrival of rescuers of 118.
"Vincenzo Valente, 46 years old, was working for an external company to the maintenance of the tape of the Brindisi sugar factory, when he underwent the amputation of the arm and died because of the severe bleeding. The dynamics of the accident is still under investigation. The incident happened after midnight today. To give the alarm were the colleagues, but on the arrival of the help for the worker there was nothing to do. Another victim. Another contract worker who loses his life torn apart by a car. Another survey to learn dynamics and responsibilities. In order to stop this massacre, the prevention and enforcement of Law 81 on safety at work, even where it allows workers to refuse to put their lives in danger, without being punishable." Andrea Gambillara, national secretary Flai Cgil, commented on the news of the death of a worker in a sugar mill in Brindisi.
"Our first thought goes to the family of the victim, to whom we express our grief and our closeness. However, alongside anger and pain, we feel the responsibility to ask, as we have done and how we will continue to do, respect for people's lives. It is necessary that the institutions and the policy (in agreement throughout its entirety) do more to find effective and immediate solutions, in particular on the delicate question concerning contracts". The national secretary Uila, Gabriele De Gasperis, declares this after the news of the death of a worker in a sugar mill in Brindisi.
For the secretary general of Uila Puglia, Pietro Buongiorno, "it is necessary to strengthen prevention and training, increase inspections and the number of inspectors of work and spread the culture of prevention that often does not represent a priority. The 'Zero morti sul lavoro' campaign promoted by the Uil is not a symbol or a propaganda slogan, it is a daily commitment we ask in all places of work, aimed at stopping this massacre that every year continues to reap more and more victims". "A drama, yet, in a poor territory of occupation, in a company in which the issues of security constitute a characteristic of the action of union protection. Waiting for the investigation to give the truth about the facts and the dynamics that have generated it, we express closeness and sympathy to the family. We shout the pain of the union and all the workers engaged in the establishment who ask for truth and justice. We cannot die of work and for the work we claim that there is more commitment and attention on the issues of safety at work", says Luigi Vizzino, territorial secretary of the Uila of Brindisi.&nbsp;
"We have been like Flai just recently at a public meeting with all the institutions in Puglia, what is happening in the workplace is a real tragedy that has precise responsibilities," adds Silvia Spera, national secretary Flai Cgil responsible for Health and Safety. " Employers do not think it necessary to invest in the safety and life of workers and workers, which is worth less than anything else. There are precise political responsibilities, having systematically depotentiated all public control and prevention systems has left free hand to the free market and to the downstream competition where human life is worth less than zero. We have legislation among the best in Europe completely disapplied, we had a public structure of work medicine among the most prestigious in Europe and left everything to die to promote the competitiveness of enterprises on the skin of those who work to live. A shame that concerns us all and calls us to assume responsibility and to react and fight because this unacceptable situation radically changes", says Spera.&nbsp;
